## Keynote Cross-Reference Protocol — CRITICAL

This is the most common source of civil takeoff errors. Follow this exactly.

### The Problem
Civil drafters reuse keynote numbers across sheets. Sheet C-101 keynote "4" = "6" PVC SDR-35 sewer. Sheet C-102 keynote "4" = "fire hydrant assembly". If you aggregate by keynote number, you get wrong counts.

### The Rule
**Build a per-sheet Keynote Master Register in Pass 1. Aggregate by `category + description` in Pass 3. Never aggregate by keynote number.**

### Per-Sheet Register Format (Pass 1 output)
```json
{
  "sheets": [
    { "sheet_number": "C-101", "title": "Utility Plan", "scale": "1\" = 20'" },
    { "sheet_number": "C-102", "title": "Grading Plan", "scale": "1\" = 20'" }
  ],
  "keynote_legend": [
    { "sheet": "C-101", "keynote": "1", "material": "8\" PVC C900 water main", "spec": "AWWA C900" },
    { "sheet": "C-101", "keynote": "4", "material": "6\" PVC SDR-35 sewer", "spec": "ASTM D3034" },
    { "sheet": "C-102", "keynote": "4", "material": "Fire hydrant assembly", "spec": "AWWA C502" }
  ]
}
```

Note: keynote "4" appears twice with different materials. This is expected and correct.

### Pass 2 Prompt Must Contain

1. The full keynote register for the current sheet
2. Explicit instruction: "Count items on THIS PAGE ONLY. Do not count items visible on other sheets."
3. Scale for this specific sheet (from register)
4. Warning: "Keynote numbers are not unique across sheets. Use the material description, not the keynote number, to identify items."

